    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-07-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-07-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="249"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d249">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 P. W./425</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by Mr. <persName type="from">Cecil W.
                            Gray</persName>, Assistant to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-07-30">July 30,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>In a telephone conversation today between Acting Secretary Welles and Secretary
                    Hull at White Sulphur Springs there was some discussion about the <hi
                        rend="italic">Tutuila</hi> bombing<note n="70" xml:id="d249fn70">See <ref
                            target="frus1941v05#pg_873">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">v</hi>, pp.
                            873</ref> ff., and <ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_719">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 719</ref>.</note> and our general
                    program of retaliatory action against Japan generally.<note n="71"
                        xml:id="d249fn71">See <ref target="#pg_774">pp. 774</ref> ff.</note> The
                    Secretary indicated that he <pb facs="0361" n="353" xml:id="pg_353"/> was quite
                    content to leave the forming of such a program to the judgment of those on the
                    ground here in Washington. His own position was summed up as being one of
                    formulating a comprehensive program of action short of war to be placed into
                    effect as rapidly as circumstances permitted.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
